A reward function R(s, a, s') is non-hackable by no-op if, for the no-op action a₀ with transition s' = s (i.e., the identity transition), R(s, a₀, s) ≤ 0 for all states s, and strictly R(s, a₀, s) < max_a R(s, a, T(s,a)) whenever a productive action exists. Equivalently, the no-op must not be a dominant or optimal policy: for every state s reachable under the optimal policy π*, a₀ ∉ argmax_a Q*(s, a), ensuring V*(s) > R(s, a₀, s) / (1−γ). More formally, letting τ_noop denote the trajectory (s₀, a₀, s₀, a₀, …) of perpetual inaction, the cumulative discounted return must satisfy Σ_{t=0}^∞ γ^t R(s₀, a₀, s₀) < V*(s₀) for all s₀, so passivity is strictly suboptimal. This is the "no free lunch for inaction" condition, a special case of the non-triviality axiom requiring that the reward not be maximized by a constant policy independent of environmental engagement.
